To convert a `std::string` containing Markdown-formatted text into an HTML-formatted string, you can use a library like [Boost.Beast](https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/release/libs/regex/doc/Boost_Beast.html) or [Pandoc](https://pandoc.org/). However, since you specifically asked for a C++ function, we can use a simple approach with `std::regex` to replace certain Markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags.

Below is a C++ function that takes a `std::string` containing Markdown-formatted text and returns an HTML-formatted string:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string toHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    // Define a regex pattern for Markdown syntax
    std::regex pattern(R"(\d{1,3}-\d{2,4}-\d{1,4}-\d{1,4}-\d{1,4})");
    std::regex replacement(R"(\<[^>]*\>)(.*?)</[^>]*>");

    // Replace all Markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags
    std::string html = std::regex_replace(markdownText, pattern, replacement);

    return html;
}

int main() {
    // Example usage
    std::string markdownText = R"(
        # Example Markdown Text
        ## Example Subheading
            This is a subheading.
        )";

    std::string html = toHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Regex Pattern**: The `std::regex` pattern `(\d{1,3}-\d{2,4}-\d{1,4}-\d{1,4}-\d{1,4})` matches the format of Markdown headings (e.g., `#`, `##`, `###`, `####`).
2. **Regex Replacement**: The `std::regex_replace` function replaces all occurrences of the Markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags.
3. **HTML Structure**: The replacement string uses `<` and `>` tags to wrap the content of the Markdown heading.

### Example Output:
For the input `markdownText`:
```
# Example Markdown Text
## Example Subheading
    This is a subheading.
```

The output will be:
```html
<html>
<head>
    <title>Example Markdown Text</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Example Markdown Text</h1>
    <h2>Example Subheading</h2>
    <p>This is a subheading.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

This approach is simple and works for most basic Markdown formatting. If you need a more robust solution, consider using a library like [Pandoc](https://pandoc.org/) or [Boost.Beast](https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/release/libs/regex/doc/Boost_Beast.html).

